history.content: Why not look at the ee126 website directly and watch the webcasts and do the discussion worksheets(if posted) and other resources on the website? It’s open so I imagine that would be useful to look st as well. 🙂

children.subject: also if you're looking to get a leg up i would maybe start reading through the same chapters of B&T that they cover in the beginning. When I started 126, i was in a similar position to you (not very good at CS70), so the first third of the class was kind of a struggle, but I survived. The second two thirds of the course were much more interesting and doable and totally made everything worth it though!

The first third of the course is CS 70 probability review (albeit with harder problems). I'd definitely recommend reviewing CS 70 probability.

Also B&T is a fantastic book with tons of problems; I'd do as many problems as possible and give it a skim before Fall Semester. Note that it doesn't assume any probability knowledge, so honestly, you could get away with just studying from that book and not touch any 70 material (notes, hw etc.). 

Doing math competition problems are unnecessary; I suck at math competitions and still got an A in this course.

history.content:
I was not very strong in CS70, so I want to take EE126 to get better at probability. What resources should I refer to over the summer to get better in preparation for 126? I'm currently thinking of:

  • Reviewing CS70 notes and doing practice problems
  • Doing online math competition probability problems
  • Looking over the course material for STAT 140

Will these be helpful? Is there anything else you recommend? Thanks!
